<h1>Kicking</h1>

<p>It's usually only the backs who need to be good kickers, but every player can spend some time after a training session practising the various types of kick.</p>

<h3>Types of kick</h3>

<p>Some kicks are for scoring points. Some are for gaining territory or relieving pressure. Other kicks can be used to get the ball behind the D-line for players to run through and gather. You can even chip the ball over or under a defender to yourself because they're not allowed to tackle you if you don't have the ball.</p>

<h5>Place kick</h5>

<p>To score a conversion or penalty you usally place the ball on a kicking tee and take a run-up to kick it through the posts.</p>

<p>There's a lot to consider when place kicking:</p>

<ul>
    <li>The angle of the kick.</li>
    <li>What kind of tee to use.</li>
    <li>Which side of the field you're on.</li>
    <li>Which foot to kick with.</li>
    <li>Where to start your run from.</li>
    <li>How to run-up.</li>
    <li>How to position the ball on the tee.</li>
    <li>How to twist your body and swing your arms to get maximum power through the ball.</li>
    <li>How high to kick it.</li>
    <li>How far to kick it.</li>
    <li>Which part of your foot should strike the ball.</li>
    <li>Which part of the ball your foot should strike.</li>
    <li>Flicking your lower leg out as it goes through the ball.</li>
    <li>Where to plant your non-kicking foot when kicking.</li>
    <li>How to keep running in case the ball hits the post and bounces back to you.</li>
    <li>What angle your body should be at.</li>
    <li>What size, shape & weight of ball you're kicking.</li>
    <li>How inflated the ball is.</li>
    <li>What kind of footwear you have.</li>
    <li>What position to swing your foot from.</li>
    <li>What position to swing your foot to.</li>
    <li>Wind speed & direction.</li>
    <li>Altitude.</li>
    <li>How tired your legs are.</li>
    <li>Putting spin on the ball to make it swerve.</li>
    <li>Blocking out distractions.</li>
</ul>

<p>Place kicking may look simple, but there's so much to think about. Most beginners may struggle to score a goal from 20m away at first, but professionals can kick accurately from 70m, maybe more. To do this, they need to perfect every aspect.</p>

