<h5>Punting</h5>

<p>You may be kicking for distance if you find yourself camped behind your 22 and you want to hoof the ball far away to relieve the pressure. When doing this, you may aim to kick into space or to an exposed player or to touch.</p>

<p>Kicking to touch means that a lineout happens further up the pitch. If you do this from a penalty, then your team gets to thrown the ball in. If you kick to touch from behind your 22, then the lineout happens where the ball crosses the touchline. If you kick directly to touch from outside your 22, then the lineout will happen from where you kicked it. Therefore, you must make sure the ball bounces in-field before going into touch when kicking from outside your 22.</p>

<p>You don't want to kick the ball over the try line unless you know you can chase it and score. If the opposition touch it down in the try area, then they'll win a dropout. The same will happen if you kick it over the dead ball or touch in goal lines.</p>

