<h3>Receiving a kick</h3>

<img class="image" src="/Images/AerialCatch.jpg">

<h5>Catching</h5>

<p>Many players choose to jump to catch a kick. This is because it's illegal to tackle a player who is in the air. You will be penalised and maybe sent-off for this kind of tackle.</p>

<p>From a kick off, some players will lift another player to catch the ball. This is so that the opposition can't tackle them, but also so there is a pod of players to support the ball-carrier when he returns to the ground.</p>

<p>Ideally, you should catch the ball sideways. This is to prevent the ball bouncing off your chest and becoming a knock-on. If you drop the ball when you're facing sideways, then the ball is more likely to fall backwards so you or your teammates have a chance to recover it.</p>

<h5>Gathering a loose ball</h5>

<p>If the ball lands on the floor and you have to race an opponent to get it, you have a few options. You can kick it, which is called fly-hacking. You may do this to kick the ball over the tryline to score or maybe to kick the ball off the pitch to prevent them from scoring.</p>

<p>You can also scoop the ball up while you're running. This takes some practice, but it's a great skill to develop.</p>

<p>Another option is to dive on the ball. When you do this, the opposition is not allowed to tackle you until you get to your feet. They must let you get up. So diving on the ball and slowly getting to your feet may give enough time for you teammates to get in position to support you.</p>

<h5>Charging down</h5>

<p>If you see a player attempting to kick in open play, you jump in the way of the ball. This is called charging down and isn't considered a knock on.</p>

<iframe class="video" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/OfwTF3J60tE" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<h5>Calling a mark</h5>

<p>If you catch the ball behind your 22 without it bouncing and shout "mark!" then the referee will award you a free kick. In case you're not heard by the referee, you may also hold you arm up at a right-angle to signify a free kick. Remember that the opposition will still try to tackle you until the referee blows their whistle, so continue playing until they do.</p>

<iframe class="video" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/59UHyPNos1I" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<h5>Carrying the ball over your own tryline</h5>

<p>If the opposition kicks the ball over your tryline and you touch it down, then you win a dropout 22. But if you knock it back or carry it over and touch it down then the opposition is awarded a scrum on the 5 metre line. The same rule applies if you or the opposition send or carry the ball over the dead ball line on touch in goal lines.</p>